Introduction

Levine et al.Â showed in their paper âThe logic of universalization guides moral judgementâ that people (both adults and children) sometimes make moral judgements by considering the hypothetical situation âwhat if everyone did that?â â a process that they call universalization. They contrast a computational model of universalization with other models of moral judgement in a variety of experiments that capture a kind of collective action âthreshold problemâ. In this report, I aim to replicate Study 2a in which they contrast universalizaion with rule-based, outcome-based, and pessimistic outcome models of moral judgement.

I think this study is very relevant to my interests in social responsibility and the use of counterfactuals in understanding and evaluating each otherâs actions. The original (preregistered) study was conducted via MTurk and all the stimuli are given in supplemental materials, so I will be aiming to replicate it exactly. I will be trying to recreate the left half of Figure 4 from the paper (and possibly also Figure S5 from the supplemental), and running the same statistical analyses. The main challenge will be coding the analysis since Iâve almost never analyzed data in R.

Links to this repo and the original paper.

Methods

Power Analysis

Planned Sample

Like the original study, participants will be recruited from MTurk. A smaller sample will be recruited due to financial constraints, but it will still be enough to report a result (if significant) based on a power analysis (TBD).

Materials and Procedure

Participants will be assigned to either the High Interest or the Low Interest condition and read a story about fishing as follows:

Twenty vacationers currently fish in a sustainable way, but then a new fishing hook becomes available that allows each vacationer to catch many more fish. If fewer than three vacationers start using the hook, there will be no negative consequences; if more than seven vacationers start using the hook, then there is guaranteed to be a total collapse of the fish population by summerâs end. Thus, the harm threshold occurs at three to seven interested parties. The protagonist of this vignette, John, is interested in using the new hook. Participants are asked if doing so would be morally acceptable.

The exact text shown to participants is provided in the supplemental materials with the instructions on lines 97-100, comprehension questions (exclusion crteria) on lines 97-96, the story itself on lines 174-218, and experiment questions on lines 134-145. These will all be shown in the same order and same format as the original study. The only difference is that five different stories were used in the original study while only one is selected here due to financial constraints, but this one story will still be an exact replication and the same effects will be tested.

Analysis Plan

Data will be filtered using the same exclusion crteria as the original study: participants must correctly answer some comprehension questions in order to be included. After filtering the data, Iâll average participantsâ responses (morally acceptability ratings) within the High Interest and Low Interest conditions, and compare the moral acceptability judgements between the two conditions by recreating the left half of Figure 4 from the paper. Iâll determine whether the difference is significant with the same statistical test as the original study:

Using a chi-squared analysis, we will see if subjects in the Low Interest condition are significantly more likely to say that the action is morally acceptable compared to subjects in the High Interest condition.

Lastly, like the original study, Iâll investigate whether participantsâ beliefs about rules or knowledge might explain their moral judgements instead. These were measured in the control questions.

For the âruleâ question:

There were only two subjects [out of 606 total] who answered that there was a rule on the lake forbidding the use of the hook. Judgments about the presence of a rule, therefore, do not explain subjectsâ moral permissibility judgments.

For the âknowledgeâ question:

We analyzed the knowledge question by looking at what proportion of subjects in each condition judged that no one would find out about John using the new hook (as opposed to thinking that 1 or more people would find out about it). There is a small but significant difference across the conditions â¦ (Ï2(1) = 5.41, p = .020, two-tailed, V_Cramer = .09, CI95%[.01, .17], n = 608) â¦ we conducted a logistic regression to see if answers to the knowledge question could fully explain our finding (as we indicated we would do in the preregistration document), and, in fact, they could not. Once knowledge is added into the model along with condition, there is still a highly significant effect of condition.

So for these two questions, first a chi-squared analysis will be used to determine whether there is a significant difference in participantsâ answers by condition. If there is none, like for the rule question in the original study, then I can conclude that factor cannot explain peopleâs moral acceptability judgements. If there is a significant difference, like for the knowledge question, then logistic regression with and without that factor can be conducted and compared to determine whether condition is still the main predictor of moral acceptability. If the same results are found in this replication as in the original study, then I should be able to recreate Figure S5 from the supplemental.

Differences from Original Study

The recruiting process, materials, and experimental procedure used in this replication report will be the same as those in the original study. The only difference is that it will effectively be a replication at a smaller scale: less participants will be recruited and only one of five stories will be used. However, given that (1) the authors of the original study still found a significant result within each story, (2) their full model found no effect of which story was used, and (3) their combined results were very significant (p<0.001), I donât anticipate that this difference will make a large impact based on the claims in the original paper.

data_filtered <- data %>%
  # Q1: include if answer is 19 && condition is high, or if answer is 0 && condition is low
  filter((exclude1 == '19' & condition == 'high') | (exclude1 == '0' & condition == 'low')) %>%
  # Q2: include if answer is 19, 20, or 21
  filter(exclude2 %in% c('19', '20', '21')) %>%
  # Q3: include if answer is 0
  filter(exclude3 == '0') %>%
  # Q4: include if answer is C (multiple choice A, B, or C)
  filter(grepl('It will not make a difference to the fish population.', exclude4))

#### Prepare data for analysis - create columns etc.
data_filtered <- data_filtered %>%
  mutate(acceptability01 = ifelse(acceptability == 'Yes', 1, 0)) %>%
  group_by(condition) %>%
  summarise(m = mean(acceptability01),
            stdev= sd(acceptability01),
            se = stdev/sqrt(n()),
            upper= m+se*1.96,
            lower=m-se*1.96)
